prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: B6 continuum/line: BAL vs nonBAL quasars, Region 1
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: This is a project to measure the dust continuum in quasar hosts with and without broad absorption lines (BALs). We are testing the idea that BAL quasars are a phase in the life of a quasar rather than just an orientation effect. If BAL quasar absorption arises at a certain evolutionary phase of a quasar then models suggest that BAL quasars should have a higher dust contribution when compared to the control sample that do not show BAL troughs, because BALs are present at a time when the host galaxy is undergoing more intense star formation.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Receiver: Band 6 (221 GHz)
Spectral Resolution: FDM mode with spectral averaging of 16 for a total bandwidth of 4x1875 MHz and a resolution of 7.813 MHz. This setup gives the same data rates as TDM though with a factor of 4 better resolution (~10 km/s versus 40 km/s).
Correlator: We set LO1 to the lowest possible value in Band 6 (221 GHz). Doing so maximizes the chance of the CO J=6-5 transition falling in one of the sidebands (~15% of our targets), since the average redshift of the sample is 2.12. Our primary goal is to characterize the difference between the cool dust continuum of BAL and non-BAL quasar hosts. However, to ensure maximum scientific output we request FDM mode with spectral averaging of 16 which gives the same data rates (also, aggregate bandwidth sensitivity and total time requested) as TDM though with a factor of 4 better resolution (~10 km/s versus 40 km/s).

Angular Resolution: 1" at Band 6. The ACA is not needed for these observations since the sources are small. High resolution for these observations is not critical, as we are measuring integrated SFRs over the entire host galaxy.
LAS: Assuming a typical galaxy size of ~15 kpc, at our lowest redshift this corresponds to an angular size of ~1.8". In order to ensure we detect scales encompassing the entire host galaxy of each of our targets, for fair comparison between them, our largest angular size requirement is 2".

Receiver(s): Band 6 (221 GHz) *We note that while we include peak line fluxes and widths for line sensitivity calculations, these are not our primary observational goal. It is our hope that we can detect CO lines in a subset of our sources serendipitously to increase our scientific output. Our primary science will be performed using continuum measurements, and so these drive our sensitivity requirements and exposure times.*
Spectral Resolution: FDM mode with spectral averaging of 16 for a total bandwidth of 4x1875 MHz and a resolution of 7.813 MHz. This setup gives the same data rates as TDM though with a factor of 4 better resolution (~10 km/s versus 40 km/s).
Continuum (Band 6) Sensitivity: Up to 150 sources may be observed in one science goal, provided the sources are less than 10 degrees apart. In the sky observable by ALMA, we find the two regions with the highest number of BAL quasars within a 5 degree radius (10 degree diameter). Each region contains 22 BAL quasars. For our control sample we center on the two regions defined by the BAL samples and match non-BAL quasars within 4% of redshift and i-band magnitude. Each region contains 22 non-BAL quasars. The two regions contain 44 quasars each.
The dust continuum flux density can be estimated via Scoville 2012 (equation 8.26). This equation relates the mass of the ISM, redshift, frequency of observations and luminosity distance to the dust continuum flux density. The flux density is lowest at z~1 and increases at lower and higher redshift. Therefore, we make minimum flux density estimates using the minimum redshift of our sample, z=1.7. We calculate the mass of the ISM by scaling the black hole mass by the Mbulge-to-Mbh ratio and gas-to-stellar mass ratio. The bulge mass is chosen to be consistent with Mbh-Mbulge relation, where the minimum expected black hole mass is chosen to be 10^8 solar masses. We use the bulge mass as a proxy for the host galaxy stellar mass. High mass systems have lower gas to stellar mass ratios. Using a gas to stellar mass ratio of 3, we estimate the minimum ISM mass to be 2x10^11 solar masses. Therefore, these sources should have S230GHz > 2.1 mJy. We aim to get a S/N ~ 20, though because of our conservative estimates on the flux density we will likely get much higher S/N.
Band 6 Observing Time: For Band 6, the ALMA sensitivity calculator, assuming thirty-six 12-m antennas and dual polarization, predicts 1.61 minutes integration per source to reach a 1 sigma = 0.1 mJy in the aggregate band. Each science goal of 44 sources would require about 1.18 hours of on-source integration, and 47.5 min of calibration and 14.4 minutes of overhead for a total of 2.21 hours per science goal (region). Our overheads are ~20% of the total time requested, which is well below the suggested <30% in the ALMA Proposer's Guide.
Line Detections: We input 0.3 mJy as our expected peak line flux to illustrate the weakest lines we can hope to detect. As stated by the exposure time calculator, at this peak line flux the S/N over the whole line (typically ~200 km/s) is ~1.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Broad Absorption Line (BAL) quasars have been studied for several decades but still remain somewhat of an enigma. What is known for certain is that they contain massive, high-velocity outflows that are a factor in the evolution of the quasar and host galaxy. Once thought to be present in all quasars but only seen when the line of sight intersected an equatorial disk wind, recent work strongly indicates that the BAL phenomenon is based not just on orientation but also on time. In such evolutionary scenarios, it is expected that the environments and host galaxies of BAL and non-BAL quasars differ, with some models predicting a higher star formation rate in BAL quasars. Previous work has used stacking analyses of FIR images to argue that BAL and non-BAL quasar hosts do not differ. With ALMA we now have the ability to 1) Directly detect large samples of individual sources instead of relying on average sample properties 2) probe longer wavelengths where the SED is entirely due to the host and not contaminated by hot dust near the quasars, and 3) study correlations between quasar and host properties. ALMA allows us to dig where previous works have only scratched the surface.
